    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.37b.6"/>
                
                <note>ans 8-29-73</note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">6</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        225 Willard Way 
                        Ithaca, <hi rend="caps">N.Y.</hi> 14850
                        August 20, 1973
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear John:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>When I received that copy of your early autobiography, I read it at once and liked it immensely. Recently, howeve<del>,</del><add>r</add>, I read it again slowly and carefully, savoring every thought and every felicity of expression. It is surely a beautiful and wonderful book. How in the world did you do it at 92? Surely there has been no deterioration in you.</p>
                
                <p>Let me call your attention to two or three high points. I liked the B<add>a</add>ttle of Wisner. What an event, and how nat<del>ionally</del><add>urally</add> it arose out of the circumstances of the moment. And what a picture <del>of convoys</del> <add>it conveys</add> of an earlier and a rougher time when men were <hi rend="underline">men</hi>.</p> 
                
                <p>I was touched deeply by the beautiful story of your speech in honor of Professor Conn, and by your dea<del>l</del><add>r</add> Mona's interest and encouragement. And there is something else - your father. There was not much about him. There coudn't be. But the glimpses given of him and his tragedy were those of a fine person. He was not with you long, yet I wonder whether all unconsciously his influence on you was not considerable and all to the good. Somehow as I read about him, I felt that I both understood and liked him.</p> 
                
                <p>As ever with the old affection.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Slade</signed> 
                    <signed>M. Slade Kendrick</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P. S.</hi></opener> <list><item><add>1</add> I have a friend in whose heart poetry wells almost without a break. I am sending some s<add>a</add>mples <note type="authorial" place="left margin">samples</note>. What do you think of them? If you like them, have you any ideas on publication?</item> 
                
                    <item>2. The tear was the result of an accidnet, but the reading was not disturbed</item></list>
                </postscript>
                
                <fw>1</fw>
                
            </div1>
